luence, and the crucial yet often overlooked role mentoring plays in their rise to the top. In the course of this book, he traces the careers of approximately four hundred of the country's most notable politicians, military officers, clergy, intellectuals, and capitalists. Thoroughly researched and drawn from in-depth interviews with some of Mexico's most powerful players, Mexico's Mandarins provides insight into the machinations of Mexican leadership and an important glimpse into the country's future as it steps onto the global stage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aElite (Social sciences)zMexicovInterviews. 0aElite (Social sciences)zMexico. 0aLeadershipzMexico. 0aMentoringzMexico. 0aSocial networkszMexico. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  a21st century.  aanthropology.  acapitalists.  acareer.  aclergy.  acontemporary mexico.  acultural social.  aeconomists.  aelite class.  aglobalization.  ainfluential people.  aintellectuals.  alatin american studies.  amandarins.  amexican history.  amexican leaders.  amexican society.  amexico scholars.  amexico.  amilitary officers.  amodern history.  anonfiction study.  anonfiction.  apersonal interviews.  apolitical power.  apoliticians.  apower elite.  aretrospective.  asocial climb.  asocietal influences.  atextbooks.  aupper class.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023344740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093638640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520936386423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520936386/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  a